Apul. met. XI 17 speaks of the people kissing the vestiqia of Isis' silver statue, as to-day in St Peter's they kiss the toe of the bronze statue of St Peter. It may be presumed then that the Romans used the right hand of their statues, as Pliny says the Greeks used the chin. 318 the meaning is by the touch of the great numbers who in passing kiss: the words rather imply ‘ of those who often kiss’: but it comes in the end to the same thing. 321 praeclusit: this verb he uses v 373 in its literal sense of shutting the door against.
